[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'When you\'re spinning up a new project, and you need a database, what\'s the first option that comes to mind? SQLite? It\'s probably SQLite, right? I mean, it\'s great, and it\'s reliable. It has zero config. It\'s an industry standard. But, as our local data gets heavier, and'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'our queries get more complex, we\'re starting to hit that ceiling of what a single-threaded file locking engine can do. But, now there\'s a new player in town that\'s trying to solve these issues. It\'s called Stu l ap, and it\'s a'

[00:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'database engine written entirely in Rust, and it just released a native Node.js driver that is, quite frankly, showing some really strong performance. The database is 138'

[00:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'times faster than SQLite. So, in this video, we\'re going to take a look under the hood of Stu l ap, see how it works, and run a live benchmarking test to see if it\'s really as powerful as it claims'

[00:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to be. It\'s going to be a lot of fun, so let\'s dive into it. So, what exactly is Stu l ap? Well, at its core, Stu l ap is an embedded OLAP,'

[01:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'or online analytical processing database. Now, if you\'re used to standard databases like SQLite or Postgres, those are typically OLTP, or online transaction processing'

[01:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'databases, which are, as the name suggests, optimized for transactions. But, Stu l ap is different. It\'s designed for analytical workloads, and it\'s built from the ground up in Rust, focusing on high-speed data processing.'

[01:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Think of it as having the portability of a SQLite file, but with the raw analytical power of something like a DuckDB or BigQuery. But, the coolest thing is that you can now use it with'

[01:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Node.js, thanks to its native Node driver. Now, when I say it\'s a native driver, I\'m not talking about some standard wrapper. Usually, when a database is written in a different language like Rust or C++, your Node.js app has to talk to it over a bridge.'

[01:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Often, that means converting your data into JSON or some other format, sending it over a local network socket, and then converting it back on the other side. That is called serialization overhead,'

[02:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and it\'s a massive performance killer. But, Steel App Node does things differently. It uses Napi RS, which is a framework that allows the Rust engine to be compiled into a native binary that'

[02:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'loads directly into your Node.js process. So, there\'s no bridge and no translator in between. When you send a query, Node.js and Rust are essentially sharing the same memory space. And,'

[02:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'there are three big reasons why Steel App is blazingly fast. First, it\'s using MVCC or multi-version concurrency control. Unlike SQLite, where a single writer can lock the entire database,'

[02:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Steel App allows multiple readers and writers to work at the same time. Secondly, it uses parallel execution. Steel App uses a scheduler called Rayon. And, with Rayon, when you run a massive'

[02:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'query, instead of sitting on one CPU core, it breaks that query apart and utilizes every core your machine has. And, thirdly, it uses a cost-based optimizer. So, it doesn\'t just execute'

[03:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'your SQL blindly, it actually analyzes your data, estimates the cost of different paths, and picks the fastest way to get to your results. So, that\'s what supposedly makes Steel App a much'

[03:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'faster option than SQLite. But, let\'s test it out to see if that\'s actually true. For this test, we\'ll be using a simple Node.js project, and we will install both Steel App and SQLite as dependencies. So, one of the biggest'

[03:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'wins where Steel App really shines is using count distinct. So, I\'m really curious to know if that really is the case. So, I set up this simple script where we spin up an in-memory version of each database and create a simple sales'

[03:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'table. We then populate this table with 10,000 rows of random sales data, where each row represents a sale from a user whose ID can vary from 0 to 1,000 and which has one of the specific'

[03:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'categories. We will then batch insert the data in both databases and then run the benchmark where we select a distinct count of sales made by a specific user on a specific category and calculate the'

[04:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'performance of each database. Now, I do have to note that it is a bit frustrating that as of now the package install does not work. If we run the benchmark test now, we see that it\'s complaining about a missing native'

[04:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'binding. So, the project\'s author clearly forgot to add the binaries or link the correct ones to the package. So, what I had to do is build it from the source. So, I cloned the repo, ran the build inside of it, and then hop'

[04:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'back to my benchmark project and linked my source directory as the dependency. This is a bit frustrating at the moment, so I hope the authors of the project will fix this in the future. But nonetheless, after doing so, we\'re now'

[04:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'finally able to run the benchmark. So, let\'s do that now. As you can see, the count distinct operation is indeed a lot faster on Stuw App, although not as much as advertised. It\'s only four times'

[05:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'faster. So, what if we add another zero to the number of data we want to populate and then run the test again with 1 million rows. So, let\'s try that now. So, even for a million rows, Stuw App is only six times faster, not 138'

[05:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'times. But nevertheless, it\'s still a great result. So, that\'s the count distinct test. I decided to do another benchmark test to test how the distinct plus order by operation. And in this'

[05:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'second test, I did a setup where we ingest some random logs with different IP addresses and status codes and then try to find distinct logs by IP address and status code pair and then order them'

[05:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'by IP ascending and status code descending. And as you can see, once we run this test, Steel Lap still performs better than SQLite, but not by 14 times, just one to 1.5 times faster. So, the'

[05:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'measurements listed here are a bit inflated in my opinion, but nevertheless, Steel Lap is indeed faster than SQLite as we just saw in the tests. To be fair, the author also mentions'

[06:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'areas where SQLite still performed better than Steel Lap, and these are mostly situations where you perform single row operations. So, Steel Lap is great for analytical and complex queries. So, is Steel Lap the SQLite'

[06:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'killer? Well, honestly, no. They\'re built for totally different things. SQLite is still your reliable daily driver for transactions, but Steel Lap might be your high-performance race car'

[06:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for data analysis. But, the fact that we now have a pure Rust analytical engine that we can now drop into a Node.js project with Napi-RS is pretty great. The project owners just got to make sure'

[06:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'they patch their current NPM package, so we don\'t have to build it from source. So, there you have it, folks. That is Steel Lap in a nutshell. But, what do you think about it? Is the performance boost worth switching to Steel Lap, or'

[06:58] [scene:talk]
